passages.text: Consumer | Global Retailing, Softlines & Luxury Brands
Outperform | Target Price/Base Case: \(\) 640.00\(from\) \ \(595.00\)
Company StatisticsMarket Capitalization (M)$23,56852-Week Range$309.01 - $534.10
1 Year Price History

A Statement Quarter in 2Q: ULTA's 2Q results were at a minimum a thesis- changer for skeptics that the company has returned to durable share gain mode after 2 years of losses. SSS growth at \(+6.7\%\) was far above expectation (EVR: \(+3\%\) , Street: \(+2.9\%\) , Bogey \(+5\%\) ), and while EPS beat significantly (\\(5.78 vs our\)\\(5.20\) , Street\)\\(5.10\) , ULTA clearly pulled forward investment, with SG&A \(+15\%\) YOY in the quarter.

Holding Back a Re- Emerging Profitability Machine: ULTA raised FY25E EPS by \(+5\%\) even while raising planned SG&A growth from \(+10\%\) YOY previously to now \(+13 - 14\%\) . EPS is now guided to \(\) 23.85- 24.30\(\) (\)22.65- \(\) 23.20\(prior). Importantly, ULTA raised FY25 SSS guidance to \(+2.5 - 3.5\%\) from flat to \(+1.5\%\) previously — implying that SSS in 2H will decelerate to \(+0.5\%\) to \(+2.4\%\) from \(+6.7\%\) in 2Q. Further, with ticket consistently growing \(+2.3\%\) , we think ULTA's 2H guidance assumes either traffic will abruptly turn negative YOY or that it's hard- fought return to share gains will reverse again—both are scenarios that we think will prove overly conservative. We raise our 2025E EPS to\)\\(25.50\) from \(\) 25.00\(previously (further above the Street at\)\\(23.68\)
Looking Beyond 2025: ULTA's model has significant noise starting in 2H and into 2026 from:

1) Target Exit: Target is "significantly less than \(1\%\) of revenues" with \(60 - 65\%\) flow through. We think the EPS loss is most likely contemplated to start in 2H25 (with both parties realizing the partnership is in wind down)—and likely embedded in some of ULTA's conservative update to FY25 EPS.
2) Mexico Expansion Begins: ULTA's partner in Mexico opened the first store under the JV in recent weeks. We see an opportunity for \(>100\) stores over time (high margin royalty. revs).

3) Space NK: 3Q will be the first full quarter including the UK acquisition. In its last reported fundamentals, that business was comping in the high 20s (could add \(\sim 50bp\) tailwind to ULTA's SSS if consolidated), but only had \(5.5\%\) operating margins.
4) Marketplace: Brand contacts are very optimistic on the launch in 3Q. We expect marketplace to start slow
(\~100 brands), but should be high margins for ULTA and accretive to EPS after some startup costs in 2H25.

But ULTA was clear that 2025 is still considered the investment year, which we think means there's opportunity for margins to expand slightly beyond the 12% target this year into 2026. As such, we think the underlying strength in the core business, and the counterbalancing effects of the inputs above are starting to make a $30.00 upside case more reasonable. We raise our 2026 EPS further above Consensus to $29.50 (prior $29.00, Street was $26.24).

- **2Q25 By the Numbers:** 2Q SSS increased +6.7% (Street +2.9%; EVRe +3.0%) and revenues +9.3% YOY (Street +4.9%; EVRe +4.8%). GM 39.2% beat the Street/EVRe 38.1%/38.2%, while SG&A rate at 26.6% was ~in line with Street/EVRe 26.7/26.5%. EPS at $5.78 was well above the Street/EVRe $5.10/$5.20.

- **EVR Estimates:** We model 3Q EPS at $4.90 (Street $4.44) on SSS +4% (Street +1.2%), GM 39.7% (Street 39.2%), and SG&A 28.8% of revenues (Street 29.2%). We raise our FY25 EPS to $25.50 (prev. $25.00; Street $23.68, guide is $23.85 to $24.30) and raise our above Street EPS for FY26/27 to $29.50/32.50 (prev. $29.00/$32.00, Street $26.24/28.80).

- **Valuation:** We raise our target price to $640 (from $595), a +8% increase, based on: 1) Rolling forward to be based on our '27E EPS (adds +6%), 2) Raising our '27E EPS to $32.50 from $32.00 (adds +2%), and 3) maintaining our target P/E at 20x. Reiterate Outperform.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:
Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.
In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.
Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.

Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances.

Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
